{"name":"Mathlib.Analysis.Calculus.Series","instances":[],"imports":["Init","Mathlib.Analysis.Calculus.UniformLimitsDeriv","Mathlib.Analysis.Calculus.ContDiff","Mathlib.Data.Nat.Cast.WithTop"],"declarations":[{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.lean#L258-L296","name":"contDiff_tsum_of_eventually","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.html#contDiff_tsum_of_eventually","doc":"Consider a series of functions `∑' i, f i x`. Assume that each individual function `f i` is of\nclass `C^N`, and moreover there is a uniform summable upper bound on the `k`-th derivative\nfor each `k ≤ N` (except maybe for finitely many `i`s). Then the series is also `C^N`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.lean#L231-L252","name":"contDiff_tsum","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.html#contDiff_tsum","doc":"Consider a series of functions `∑' i, f i x`. Assume that each individual function `f i` is of\nclass `C^N`, and moreover there is a uniform summable upper bound on the `k`-th derivative\nfor each `k ≤ N`. Then the series is also `C^N`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.lean#L220-L225","name":"iteratedFDeriv_tsum_apply","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.html#iteratedFDeriv_tsum_apply","doc":"Consider a series of smooth functions, with summable uniform bounds on the successive\nderivatives. Then the iterated derivative of the sum is the sum of the iterated derivative. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.lean#L196-L215","name":"iteratedFDeriv_tsum","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.html#iteratedFDeriv_tsum","doc":"Consider a series of smooth functions, with summable uniform bounds on the successive\nderivatives. Then the iterated derivative of the sum is the sum of the iterated derivative. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.lean#L185-L189","name":"fderiv_tsum","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.html#fderiv_tsum","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.lean#L179-L182","name":"fderiv_tsum_apply","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.html#fderiv_tsum_apply","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.lean#L167-L176","name":"differentiable_tsum","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.html#differentiable_tsum","doc":"Consider a series of functions `∑' n, f n x`. If all functions in the series are differentiable\nwith a summable bound on the derivatives, then the series is differentiable.\nNote that our assumptions do not ensure the pointwise convergence, but if there is no pointwise\nconvergence then the series is zero everywhere so the result still holds. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.lean#L155-L160","name":"hasFDerivAt_tsum","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/Series.html#hasFDerivAt_tsum","doc":"Consider a series of functions `∑' n, f n x`. If the series converges at a\npoint, and all functions in the series are differentiable with a summable bound on the derivatives,\nthen the series is differentiable and its derivative is the sum of the derivatives. "},{"sourceLink":"https://githu